Task #50 (the G-7b audit F2 seam): create-mode fopen / the unlink
family -- openat O_CREAT wired through SYS_WALK_CREATE (= 54) + the
unlinkat boundary-line over SYS_UNLINK (= 58).

The 0021 openat refused O_CREAT/O_TMPFILE with ENOTSUP (fail-closed;
create-mode fopen never worked in pouch), so fopen(path,"w"/"a") and
tmpfile() returned NULL -- interactive TyrQuake's config.cfg / demo
record did not persist. This patch:

  src/fcntl/openat.c        The O_CREAT arm: open-existing first
      (unless O_EXCL); on ENOENT split the path, T_OPATH-open the
      parent (born-R|W -- the A-1.7 navigation base; #81 blocks only
      its byte I/O, never create/unlink), SYS_WALK_CREATE the single
      base component (perm = mode & 0777; no pouch umask surface), and
      resolve an EEXIST-race by retrying the plain open once (the #99
      honest-errno pattern). ALSO: O_TRUNC now maps to T_OTRUNC (the
      prior silent no-op made fopen("w") overwrite-in-place on an
      existing file -- a correctness fix, not just the create arm),
      and O_APPEND seeks to END after any successful open
      (single-writer append; no kernel append mode, so concurrent-
      append atomicity is documented-absent). O_TMPFILE proper stays
      ENOTSUP (musl's tmpfile() uses O_CREAT|O_EXCL, never it).

  src/unistd/unlinkat.c     The real boundary-line body: split,
      T_OPATH parent, SYS_UNLINK(parent, base, len, flags);
      AT_REMOVEDIR -> SYS_UNLINK_REMOVEDIR (0x200). Trailing slashes
      legal on a directory target; "/" itself answers EBUSY. The 0014
      /srv short-circuit is PRESERVED here (this patch replaces the
      0014 unlink.c body, so the carve moves into the chokepoint all
      of unlink/rmdir/remove route through): a plain unlink of
      /srv/<name> answers 0 -- the per-boot kernel registry has no
      file artifact, and stratumd's listen prologue treats any
      non-ENOENT unlink failure as fatal (the first gate run proved
      it: dropping the carve killed the stratumd-boot at 16c).

  src/unistd/unlink.c       musl's bodies are RAW
  src/unistd/rmdir.c        __syscall(SYS_unlinkat, ...) -- the
  src/stdio/remove.c        unwired 0xFFFF sentinel -- so each is
  src/stdio/tmpfile.c       rerouted through the public unlinkat()/
      unlink() (the 0023 sys_open-reroute precedent). tmpfile()'s
      immediate unlink now works: the open fd keeps the file alive
      (the Plan 9-lineage fid-survives-unlink property, proven live by
      /pouch-hello-fopen's tmpfile leg -- write/rewind/read AFTER the
      unlink).

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in   __NR_walk_create 54 +
      __NR_unlink_component 58 (custom seam names -- the kernel ABI
      differs from Linux unlinkat's, so the real __NR_unlinkat stays
      the 0xFFFF sentinel and raw callers keep failing honestly).

Untested-in-guest at v1.0: the rmdir/AT_REMOVEDIR arm (pouch has no
mkdir surface to create a removable directory; the kernel SYS_UNLINK
REMOVEDIR path carries its own kernel tests). Proven by
/pouch-hello-fopen (create/append/truncate/excl/unlink/remove/tmpfile,
boot-fatal, post-pivot on the Stratum FS) and live by TyrQuake's
config.cfg persisting across the play-leg quit.

